label.value: positive regulation of meiotic cell cycle

definition.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of progression through the meiotic cell cycle.

label.value: negative regulation of meiotic cell cycle

definition.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of progression through the meiotic cell cycle.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH), a peptide hormone responsible for the release of follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH) from the anterior pituitary. GnRH is synthesized and released by the hypothalamus.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with thyrotropin-releasing hormone, a tripeptide hormone that stimulates the release of thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) and prolactin by the anterior pituitary and it is produced by the hypothalamus and travels across the median eminence to the pituitary via the pituitary portal system.

The multiplication or reproduction of myoblasts, resulting in the expansion of a myoblast cell population. A myoblast is a mononucleate cell type that, by fusion with other myoblasts, gives rise to the myotubes that eventually develop into skeletal muscle fibers.

label.value: attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochore involved in homologous chromosome segregation

definition.value: The process in which spindle microtubules become physically associated with the proteins making up the kinetochore complex during meiosis I. During meiosis I sister kinetochores are lying next to each other facing the same spindle pole and monopolar attachment of the chromatid to the spindle occurs.

label.value: attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochore involved in meiotic sister chromatid segregation

definition.value: The process in which spindle microtubules become physically associated with the proteins making up the kinetochore complex during meiosis II. During meiosis II sister kinetochores are situated facing opposite spindle poles and bipolar attachment of the sister chromosomes to the spindle occurs.

Catalysis of the transfer of ectoine from one side of the membrane to the other. Ectoine (1,4,5,6-tetrahydro-2-methyl-4-pyrimidinecarboxylic acid) is a tetrahydropyrimidine commonly synthesized by halophilic bacteria.
Catalysis of the transfer of a glucosylglycerol from one side of the membrane to the other. A glucosylglycerol is an alpha-D-glucopyranosyl-alpha-(1,2)-glycerol.
Catalysis of the transfer of a mannosylglycerate from one side of the membrane to the other.

label.value: activation of anaphase-promoting complex activity involved in meiotic cell cycle

definition.value: Any process that initiates the ubiquitin ligase activity of the anaphase-promoting complex during the meiotic cell cycle.
Catalysis of the reaction -  geranylgeranyl diphosphate -eq- 9alpha-copalyl diphosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  D-aminoacyl-tRNA -eq- D-amino acid + tRNA. Hydrolysis of the removal of D-amino acids from residues in charged tRNA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  D-tyrosyl-tRNA(Tyr) -eq- D-tyrosine + tRNA(Tyr). Hydrolysis of the removal of D-tyrosine from tyrosine residues in charged tRNA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-glucose + a sterol -eq- UDP + O-glucosyl-cholesterol.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-glucose + a sterol -eq- UDP + O-glucosyl-ergosterol.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-glucose + a sterol -eq- UDP + O-glucosyl-beta-sitosterol.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-glucose + a sterol -eq- UDP + O-glucosyl-stigmasterol.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-glucose + a sterol -eq- UDP + O-glucosyl-tomatidine.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with NFAT (nuclear factor of activated T cells) proteins, a family of transcription factors. NFAT proteins have crucial roles in the development and function of the immune system.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with an iron-sulfur cluster, a combination of iron and sulfur atoms.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a 2 iron, 2 sulfur (2Fe-2S) cluster -  this cluster consists of two iron atoms, with two inorganic sulfur atoms found between the irons and acting as bridging ligands.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a 3 iron, 4 sulfur (3Fe-4S) cluster -  this cluster consists of three iron atoms, with the inorganic sulfur atoms found between the irons and acting as bridging ligands. It is essentially a 4Fe-4S cluster with one iron missing.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a 4 iron, 4 sulfur (4Fe-4S) cluster -  this cluster consists of four iron atoms, with the inorganic sulfur atoms found between the irons and acting as bridging ligands.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a cluster of atoms including both metal ions and nonmetal atoms, usually sulfur and oxygen. Examples include iron-sulfur clusters and nickel-iron-sulfur clusters.
Catalysis of the reaction -  anthocyanidin 3-glucoside + UDP-rhamnose -eq- anthocyanidin 3-rutinoside + UDP.

Catalysis of the beta-elimination of the 5' deoxyribose-5-phosphate at an abasic site in DNA where a DNA-(apurinic or apyrimidinic site) lyase has already cleaved the C-O-P bond 3' to the apurinic or apyrimidinic site.

A checkpoint that acts during late prophase I (pachytene) and prevents segregation of homologous chromosomes until recombination is completed, ensuring proper distribution of the genetic material to the gametes.
Any process in which is the spindle is transported to, and|or maintained in, a specific location.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of terminal, non-reducing 2,1- and 2,6-linked beta-D-fructofuranose residues in fructans.
Catalysis of the endohydrolysis of 2,1-beta-D-fructosidic linkages in inulin.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of pullulan to isopanose (6-alpha-maltosylglucose).
Any process in which the spindle is maintained in a specific location within a cell and prevented from moving elsewhere.
Catalysis of the reaction -  L-saccharopine + O2 -eq- L-2-aminoadipic 6-semialdehyde + L-glutamate + H2O2.
Catalysis of the reaction -  L-proline + O2 + H2O -eq- L-delta1-pyrroline-5-carboxylate + H2O2.
Catalysis of the reaction -  fructosyl-amino acid + O2 -eq- corresponding amino acid + glucosone + H2O2.
Catalysis of the reaction -  inositol-1,3,4,5-tetrakisphosphate + H2O -eq- inositol-1,4,5-trisphosphate + phosphate.

label.value: DNA (cytosine-5-)-methyltransferase activity, acting on CpG substrates

definition.value: Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + CpG (in DNA) -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + 5-MeCpG (in DNA).

label.value: DNA (cytosine-5-)-methyltransferase activity, acting on CpN substrates

definition.value: Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + DNA containing CpN -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + DNA containing 5-MeCpN.

label.value: DNA (cytosine-5-)-methyltransferase activity, acting on CpNpG substrates

definition.value: Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + DNA containing CpNpG -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + DNA containing 5-MeCpNpG.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the enzyme protein phosphatase 2A.
Catalysis of the reaction -  C-terminal protein amino acid methyl ester + H2O -eq- protein amino acid + methanol.
Catalysis of the reaction -  protein amino acid methyl ester + H2O -eq- protein amino acid + methanol.
Enables the directed movement of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide into, out of or within a cell, or between cells -  transport may be of either the oxidized form, NAD, or the reduced form, NADH.
Any process that modulates the rate or extent of progression through the cell cycle.

label.value: cell cycle switching, mitotic to meiotic cell cycle

definition.value: The process in which a cell switches cell cycle mode from mitotic to meiotic division.

label.value: germline cell cycle switching, mitotic to meiotic cell cycle

definition.value: The process in which a germline cell switches cell cycle mode from mitotic to meiotic division.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GTP + 5'-dephospho-RNA -eq- GDP + 5'-phospho-RNA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  NTP + 5'-dephosphopolynucleotide -eq- NDP + 5'-phosphopolynucleotide. The polynucleotide may be DNA or RNA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  NTP + 5'-dephospho-RNA -eq- NDP + 5'-phospho-RNA.
